deck_excerpt: It took a while to make a deck with Millennium Eyes that was competitively viable, but with careful card consideration, this build should be the most
deck_description: It took a while to make a deck with Millennium Eyes that was competitively viable, but with careful card consideration, this build should be the most reliable Millennium-based deck that you will find. The primary reason for this is that it completely skips the idea of getting relinquished itself ritual summoned, as ritual spells tend to do little more than unnecessarily clog the deck.  With this deck, you rely on searches, draws, and sending the fusion pieces to grave and careful card play to stun your opponent on the second turn. With Dragonic Magic in the deck, it gets a nice buff for the first turn if you have Illusionist Magician in grave. As you can see, the card advantage tends to be very good since you can use Allure, Pot of Desires after sending some monsters to grave, and use Dark World Dealings with little downside (since your fusion spell fusions from the grave). If played carefully, you can get Thousand Restrict on the board as well, which can result in an almost total monster lock.  Play the cards carefully, and try to maintain 1 copy of each of Ill. Magician, Illusionist, and Relinquished in the grave or hand, if possible. Your opponent may try to bait you by throwing out an effect he/she doesn't need, so be wary of this.

deck_excerpt: Going Second Gouki Spyral 2018 (Post December 2018 Banlist)
deck_description: Happy Holidays to everyone! I have a special deck for you all tonight and more awesome decks coming up in the near future I've been preparing and testing from scratch. This deck is Going Second Gouki Spyral. You always want to go second and this deck link spams like crazy going second. This deck mains a lot of handtraps so you can go second and prevent your opponent from making their plays and then go off hardcore on your turn. It's not that hard to predict your opponent's next draw if you know the meta well and know what deck they are playing since you are going second which is why I chose to put Spyral Super Agent as an extender. Going into Gouki Heel Ogre and then Gouki The Giant Ogre is insane turn two because Giant Ogre is immune to monster effects and can make his attack higher if his attack is altered. There is a cool combo with Divine Sword and Giant Ogre where if you equip him with Divine Sword since his attack is altered you can have him gain an additional 1000 attack points. The normal going second combo for this deck is to get out Isolde and then after using her effects, go into Summon Sorceress and go into a link 4 after using her effect, then proceed to OTK since you left your opponent with hardly any resources because of all the handtraps. In addition to this, I really like using Autonomous Action Unit in this deck as a tech because going second your opponent is most likely going to have a monster in their graveyard you can special summon and use. Have a great day everyone and safe travels!

Harpie

"Harpie" ( HÄpyi) is an archetype composed of WIND Dragon and Winged Beast monsters. Mai Valentine uses this archetype in the anime and manga. "Sky Scout", originally known as "Harpie's Brother", is not a Harpie card because it does not have in its Japanese name. It was renamed to clarify this. When "Harpies" were released (some of the first monsters released that would later become an official archetype), they didn't have much support. From Rise of Destiny onward, however, "Harpies" became more balanced and powerful with occasional support cards released. Structure Deck: Lord of the Storm has aided this archetype with cards such as "Hysteric Party" and "Harpie's Pet Baby Dragon", while also featuring a lot of other Harpie-related cards in it. Afterwards, "Harpie Queen" was released in Force of the Breaker, providing ways to search for "Harpie's Hunting Ground".

deck_excerpt: A calculated approach to Trains: Japanese edition. An 89% chance of Liebe and 82% of an Anger Knuckle alongside it, but this time, with Maxx C and Veh
deck_description: Take a regular Trains deck. Now add a helping of Sky Strikers, a dash of Utopic, and smother with card draw. The end result is a deck that can OTK with ridiculous consistency!  Like with my other decks, I made a script for calculating the odds - an 88.8% chance of summoning a Rank 10 XYZ first turn and an 82.0% chance of getting an Anger Knuckle alongside it. ...Not counting the card draws from all those Maxx Cs, of course.     Playing the deck is pretty simple - first priority is summoning a Liebe (or Super Dora on turn 1), second priority is summoning an Anger Knuckle first. And always go first - it may seem counter-intuitive, but it's definitely a deck that benefits more from having a T1 than it loses from having your opponent get an extra card and attack.  Other combos to be aware of:  Anger Knuckle + Urgent Schedule: if Anger Knuckle is in the GY, you can set Schedule, then destroy it for a free Knuckle + Lv10 summoning.  Anger Knuckle/Urgent Schedule + Switchyard: summoning on your opponent's turn lets you activate Switchyard's summoning effect without the downside. It's usually two free extra summons.  Sky Strikers: the reason they're here is because Hornet Drones, using Kagari, can get you two Machine monsters out with a single card, which can then be linked into Anger Knuckle. If you can't tell yet, Anger Knuckle is essential for Trains.     Last things to mention are: Qliphort Genius and Platinum Gadget are valid candidates, but there's no Extra Deck space. Shaddoll is worth running (instead of Pots Of Desires) but only if going second (which, again, don't if you have the chance). Seven Sins and Infinity Dark Utopic are the worst of the XYZs. Upstart Goblin is quite definitely worth running even if it does mean you can't beat your opponent with a single Liebe. If your opponent Maxx Cs you after you play a Lv10, it's usually worth combining into Super Dora or Liebe anyway. And Limiter Removal/Train Connection can be run by preference, I just prefer not to.

deck_excerpt: Give yourself the best chances to OTK with Rampage
deck_description: This deck is designed to cover the weaknesses of the typical cyber OTK. It's extremely high octane and is very reckless with lifepoints to achieve the ultimate goal: huggge life point damage while going second.  Kaiju is used to get any monsters that have free negation from turn 1. Red reboot is used to negate any troublesome traps that would get in the way of your reckless Rampage Dragon for the entire turn. Double copies of Limiter Removal and triple of Power Bond ensure that most turns you will be able to get a 4200 attack Rampage that gets to have 3 attacks. Pot of Desires is the perfect card to use in this reckless play style as the +1 is well worth it.  What makes Cyber decks special is their adaptability. There is always Infinity to play more conservatively and handtraps that serve as filler to keep your opponent from stacking the board on turn 1, making your OTK even more likely.  This deck is too powerful (like most meta decks) for casual play.

deck_excerpt: Can't afford evenly matched, infinite impermanence, or borrelsword dragon? Neither can I! This build of Paleo Frogs utilizes cards that don't break th
deck_description: Can't afford evenly matched, infinite impermanence, or borrelsword dragon? Neither can I! This build of Paleo Frogs utilizes cards that don't break the bank, while still performing at a reasonably consistent rate.  I've personally decided to cut the solemn brigade down to 3 cards, as although their power is invaluable, the fact that you can't chain paleos to them means that you'll be left without paleos on board to establish toad. The addition of Lilith fixes hands with low paleo counts and searches for most of the deck, and the addition of compulsory evacuation device means you can bounce pesky monsters resistant to destruction such as the thunder dragon fusions. Reckless greed is definitely a debatable option, and I personally go back and forth between taking out out and leaving it in.

Trickstar

"Trickstar" is an archetype of female LIGHT Fairy monsters used by Skye Zaizen in the Yu-Gi-Oh! VRAINS anime, which debuted in the OCG and TCG with Code of the Duelist.  

Design

  The "Trickstar" monsters are based on Japanese idols. All of the members shown so far are females dressing in colorful attires with a few pairs of insect-like wings, glassy eyes, a tattoo of varying shape on their faces, headphones over their ears, and holding an unique object in their respective artworks. Their skirt designs resemble the petal of each flowers they're named after. Each of them also has an emblem resembles a mix of heart, skull, and butterfly, somewhere on their dress, possibly refers to the fact that majority of them are named after poisonous flowers. The Main Deck monsters have an appearance of teenage girls, while majority of the Link Monsters appear as young women. The monster "Dark Angel", although not being an official member of this archetype, has a similar design to the rest of the "Trickstar" monsters and was also used by Skye in the anime once.

Element

 

    The Element (Eremento) cards are a series of LIGHT and DARK monsters that gain two additional effects (such as ATK boost, effect negation, and double attack) when a certain Attribute is present on the field other than their own. They're all Level 4 monsters with 1500 ATK and 1200 DEF. The effects themselves are also generic:
  • FIRE provides a respectable 500 ATK boost (to 2000).
  • WATER prevents the monster from shifting to the opposing player.
  • WIND allows the monster to attack up to twice during the Battle Phase by first having destroyed another monster.
  • EARTH allows the monster to negate the effect of another monster it destroys.
No two "Element" monsters have the same combination of effects and they always depict the Attributes where they gain their effects in the background of the cards. All "Element" monsters depict in their artwork the Elements in which they gain their effects on both the monster themselves and the background the monster is in.

deck_excerpt: An updated version of Dios Neos with Neo Space Connector and the neos support found in Savage Strike that overall makes it a much more consistent deck
deck_description: Now with the added neo spacian support Neos decks can finally stand a chance at your locals. Even though neo space connector is probably a better card when not being used in it's archetypal deck, it's an amazing card in neos build letting you summon any neo spacian monster, most commonly aqua dolphin to make an Isolde and special summon shadow mist if you're going first. Or go into any of the other neos monsters to make something like air neos with air humming bird if your going second.  You'll mainly be going into Rainbow neos, and all the other 2 material neos fusions in your deck with the new Neos Fusion. Neos Fusion is probably the best piece of Neo spacian support released, as it has the effect that reads: "Â If a Fusion Monster you control that lists âElemental HERO Neosâ as material would be destroyed by battle or card effect, or returned to the Extra Deck by its own effect, you canÂ banishÂ this card from your GY instead." This is amazing,as the worst part of all neos fusions (outside of rainbow neos) is that they all send themselves back to the extra deck at the end phase. This completely bypasses that massive downside to all neos fusions and lets them stay on the field on your opponents turn, and also protects them from destruction. And it's not just one fusion summoned with Neos Fusion either nor does it limit you on just the 2 material neos fusions either. If you have a Neos Fusion in your graveyard and make a neos fusion monster with either Miracle Contact or Miracle Fusion, you can still use Neos Fusion's banish effect to protect them or keep them on the field.  Finally brave neos is a personal choice to add in the extra deck. While only boosting by 100 is a disappointment, 2500 on it's own isn't to shabby, and your bound to fave at least a few neo spacian or E-HERO monsters in your grave when it's summoned. But the big thing for me is when it destroys a monster by battle, you can add a card that lists "Elemental Hero Neos" in the card text letting you add one of the two fusion cards made for neo spacians. This lets you easily access Neos Fusion to go into Rainbow, or Air neos. Or even make Grand neos if there's a really big problem card on the field you just need to make go away. Maybe even just add Miracle Contact and make Nebua neos, get a mega ton of cards added to your hand and then banish every card on the field face down during the end phase. This makes me prefer having the Brave neos over a second Rainbow Neos, but I can understand if you want to replace the Brave Neos for a second Rainbow Neos.

deck_excerpt: 60 Card Spyral Warrior FTK (With Tutorial) (Post December 2018 Banlist)
deck_description: Wow almost a thousand views on my Burning Abyss Infernoid deck... Thank you so much guys!!! Since we reached both goals of getting 3 likes on the deck plus a comment I have made a Spyral Warrior Gumblar FTK deck from scratch. Although this deck can brick sometimes I've figured out while play testing that this is the best build I came up with after testing. You always want to go first with this deck if possible. The idea of using Red-Eyes Flare Metal Dragon and Summon Sorceress to special summon Gellenduo with its effects negated off Beatrice to your opponents field and burning until your opponent dies on the first turn is really good. The FTK is not super consistent but it is a 2 card FTK and even if you don't draw the required pieces to pull off the FTK you still have the Spyral engine to play and go into Double Helix and or Gumblar. You can even Gumblar your opponent for 6 using Aqua Dolphin twice off the new Neo Space Connector that was just released in the Soul Fusion Special Edition recently. The way that this works is you Gumblar your opponent for 2 then another 2 off Aqua Dolphin since you can use its effect twice from Neo Space Connector and get out SPYRAL Quik-Fix to go into Linkuriboh and then get back Quik-Fix from the graveyard using either its effect or Big Red or Spyral Mission Rescue etc... Then when your opponent draws you can trigger Linkuriboh in grave to summon it using Quik-Fix as the tribute which triggers Gumblars effect for another 2 cards meaning your opponent has no cards in hand! Now I will explain how the actual FTK works using Red-Eyes Flare Metal Dragon. All you need in hand is Vision HERO Vyon plus another Warrior monster. You can't have Malicious in your hand or you can't do it sadly since Mali got limited to 2. First special summon the Warrior monster in your hand then normal summon Vision HERO Vyon and use its effect to send Mali from deck to grave, then go into Isolde, Two Tales of The Noble Knights and use her effect to get whatever Warrior monster you want from deck to hand except Mali or Armageddon Knight since you need thoseÂ  later. Then use Isolde's second effect to send 4 equip spells from your deck to grave except the D.D.R's you need those, and special summon Armageddon Knight from the deck, use his effect to send Destrudo The Lost Dragon's Frisson from your deck to the graveyard. Next use Destrudo's effect to special summon himself and choose to reduce his level by Armageddon Knight's and Synchro them into Power Tool Dragon. Then use Power Tool Dragon's effect to get yourself D.D.R since there are 3 copies meaning you will automatically get it. After that you want to use Divine Sword - Phoenix Blade in your graveyard that you sent off Isolde's second effect to banish Armageddon Knight and another Warrior monster besides Mali and add it to your hand. This means you can use D.D.R to send Divine Sword to the grave as cost and special summon Armageddon Knight from the banish zone and use its effect again to send Blackwing - Zephyros The Elite and use its effect to add D.D.R back to your hand sending Armageddon Knight to the grave and special summoning Zephyros. Then you can loop Divine Sword and D.D.R again to banish Armageddon Knight and use D.D.R to send Divine Sword and special summon Armageddon Knight and use his effect to send Plaguespreader Zombie and use his effect to send a card from your hand to the top of the deck to special summon himself and then use him and Zephyros to get out Brionac, Dragon of The Ice Barrier to the other zone of Isolde. Then use Mali from grave to special summon another copy of himself from the deck and use Brionac and Mali to go into Beatrice, Lady of the Eternal and use her effect to send Overtex Quatlus from deck to grave. Then use its effect to get Double Evolution Pill from your deck to hand and use it to special summon the second Overtex Quatlus from your deck. Using it and Power Tool Dragon, go into Red-Eyes Flare Metal Dragon. After that link Armageddon Knight and Isolde to go into Summon Sorceress and use her second effect to target Beatrice and special summon Gellenduo from your deck to your opponents field negated. Then xyz Gaia Dragon, the Thunder Charger on top of Beatrice and use him and Summon Sorceress to go into the new Agave Dragon from Soul Fusion and use its effect to burn your opponent for 100 since you have a dragon type in your graveyard which will then start the infinite burn between Gellenduo and Red-Eyes Flare Metal Dragon since Gellenduo says it gets destroyed when that player takes any damage but its effects are negated so therefore it doesn't get destroyed which triggers Flare Metal Dragon since an opponent's card effect was activated and then the loop continues. There are just a ton of other cool combos you can do in general since the main Spyral monsters are Warrior type and you can use them to go into Isolde. Have fun and stay tuned for more decks! :)

Helios

 

  "Helios" is a series of sun-like LIGHT Pyro monsters named after Helios used by Lyman Banner in the Yu-Gi-Oh! GX anime. They are based around gaining ATK through piling up monsters in the Banished Zone. With the exception of "Helios Trice Megistus", all members of this series have had their artwork censored when released into the TCG.

Playing style

Note that, despite the fact that "Macro Cosmos" supports the first Helios and banishes cards, it isn't recommended because both "Duo" and "Trice" must be sent to the Graveyard to activate their effects.

Duston

 

  "Duston" ( Dasuton) is an archetype of Level 1 Fiend monsters with the appearance of dust particles that was first introduced in Abyss Rising. All monsters of this archetype have 0 ATK and 1000 DEF, except for the ? ATK and DEF "Starduston". Their play style revolves around using "House Duston" to Special Summon members of the archetype to either side of the field, ideally ones with negative effects to your opponent's side of the field and ones with positive and/or no effects to your own side of the field. This reflects how dust can spread in real life.

Cloudian

 

  "Cloudian" (ï¼Kuraudian) is an archetype used by Adrian Gecko in the Yu-Gi-Oh! GX anime. All of its members are WATER Fairy Effect Monsters, except for the following:
  • WIND Aqua - "Cloudian - Eye of the Typhoon"
  • Fiend - "Cloudian - Ghost Fog" and "Cloudian - Poison Cloud".
  • Normal Monster - "Cloudian - Smoke Ball"
They were introduced in Gladiator's Assault, with further support in Light of Destruction. Most of these monsters cannot be destroyed by battle while in Attack Position, but if in Defense Position they are instantly destroyed via their own effects. Most "Cloudians" have their effects activated or become active while they have Fog Counters.
